The paper presents a control scheme for autonomous underwater vehicles, which involves modeling and control design. The focus is on the control aspect, which suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. The use of Nonlinear Model Predictive Control (NMPC) and the incorporation of state and input constraints suggest that the paper may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. The use of ocean currents and the aim to reduce energy consumption suggest that the paper may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The use of a test tank with obstacles suggests that the paper may also belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Finally, the use of experimental verification suggests that the paper may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
